ISBN: 1602392463, 1848325029 | 2008 | EPUB | 384 pages | 890 KB

From 1933 to 1945, the Gestapo was Nazi Germany's chief instrument of counterespionage, political suppression, and terror. Jacques Delarue, a saboteur arrested by the Nazis in occupied France, chronicles how the land of Beethoven elevated sadism to a fine art. The Gestapo: A History of Horror draws upon Delarue's interviews with ex-Gestapo agents to deliver a multi-layered history of the force whose work included killing student resisters, establishing Aryan eugenic unions, and implementing the Final Solution. This is a probing look at the Gestapo and the fanatics and megalomaniacs who made it such a successful and heinous organizationÃ¢â‚¬â€Barbie, Eichmann, Himmler, Heydrich, MÃƒÂ¼ller. The Gestapo's notorious reign led to the murder of millions. The Gestapo is an important documentation of what they did and how they did it.
